library(tidyverse)
ggplot(data=mpg)

# CODE GOES HERE
View(mpg)
# CODE GOES HERE
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x=cyl, y=hwy))

  1. The drv" variable describes the wheel drive mode of a car.f means front-wheel drive, r means rear wheel drive and 4 means four wheel drive.
# CODE GOES HERE
?mpg
## starting httpd help server ... done
  1. There are only 12 data ponits left on the scatterplot graph, which illustates the existing matches of car type and wheel drive mode. This plot is not useful because class and drv are both categorical variables and information like the number of data point in each category cannot be displayed because of the overlapping of the data points.
# CODE GOES HERE
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x=drv, y=class))

2.2 grammar of graphics: Mapping data to aesthetics

  1. variable are categorical. and are continuous.
# CODE GOES HERE
?mpg
print(mpg)

  1. The two graphs are dierent because year is a continuous variable in graph 1 and year is transformed into a categorical variable through as.character(year) in graph 2. Graph 2 is a better representation of the data because the value of the variable year in our dataset just contains two discrete type: 1999 and 2008.
# CODE GOES HERE
# Graph 1 
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x=hwy, y=cty, color=year))

# Graph 2 
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = cty, color = as.character(year)))

  1. A continuous variable can not be mapped to shape but a categorical variable can. Using size for a categorical variable is not advised but using size for a continuous variable is ok.In graphs, the legends of continuous variables are displayed in a spectrum while those of categorical variables are displayed in discrete categories.
# CODE GOES HERE
# Mapping cyl to size
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = cty, size = cyl))

# Mapping cyl to shape
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = cty, shape = cyl))
# CODE GOES HERE
# Mapping drv to size
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = cty, size = drv))
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

# Mapping drv to shape
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = cty, shape = drv))

  1. The data points are displayed in two colors. Those whose engine displacement is less than 5 are categorized into TRUE and become blue. Those whose engine displacement is no less than 5 are categorized into FALSE and become pink.
# CODE GOES HERE
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = cty, color=displ<5))

5.The argument of color should be in geom_point() instead of aes() if we want to change the color of data points.

# CODE GOES HERE
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = "blue"))

2.3 grammar of graphics: Facets

  1. The layout of the grid is decided by the cols and rows arguments in facet_grid(): cols decides the horizontal arrangment of the grid while rows decides the vertical. The number of the facets to produce is decided by the product of the number of categories contained in the variables assigned to cols and rows.
# CODE GOES HERE
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + facet_grid(cols = vars(drv))

ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + facet_grid(rows = vars(year))

ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + facet_grid(rows = vars(year), cols = vars(drv))

  1. If you facet on a continuous variable, every unique value this continuous variable contains will creat a corresponding facet.
# CODE GOES HERE
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + facet_grid(cols = vars(cty))

  1. Advantage: Its easier to tell the trends and relationship in each facet. Disadvantage: It segregates the data points into different facets and make it harder to find overall trends and relationships.The number of data points in each facet may not be enough to suggest a trend. If with a larger dataset, color aestheitc will have less advantage.Because there will probably be too many color categories and makes it hard to tell the difference between the colors. There might also be too much data points overlapping. But faceting is more likely to have enough data points in each facet and represent better.
# CODE GOES HERE
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + facet_wrap(vars(year), nrow = 2)

  1. The nrow and ncol decide respectively the number of rows and columns that the faceted plot will have. Other options control the layout of the individual panels includes: scales: decides scales to be fixed, free or free in one dimension. dir: decides whether the layout of facets should be arranged in horizontal or vertical direction. shrink: If TRUE, will shrink scales to fit output of statistics, not raw data. If FALSE, will be range of raw data before statistical summary. as.table: If TRUE, the facets are laid out like a table with highest values at the bottom-right. If FALSE, the facets are laid out like a plot with the highest value at the top-right. etc.

For facet_grid, we can assign variables to cols and rows arguments to control the number of rows and columns.

# CODE GOES HERE
 ?facet_wrap
# CODE GOES HERE
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy,color=class)) + facet_wrap(vars(year), nrow = 2,strip.position="right" )

# CODE GOES HERE
 p <- ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy,color=class)) + facet_wrap(vars(year), nrow = 2,strip.position="right" )
p+theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust=1))

#https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1330989/rotating-and-spacing-axis-labels-in-ggplot2
  1. Many manufacturers are missing because the shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values and the data points of the rest 9 categories are not displayed.In addition, 112 rows containing missing values are removed.
# CODE GOES HERE
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy,shape= manufacturer)) + facet_grid(rows = vars(year), cols = vars(drv)) 
## Warning: The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values
## because more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate; you have
## 15. Consider specifying shapes manually if you must have them.
## Warning: Removed 112 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

# CODE GOES HERE
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy,shape= manufacturer)) + facet_grid(rows = vars(year), cols = vars(drv)) +scale_shape_manual(values = 1:15)
